FAQs

Is it expensive to study in Ireland?

Tuition fees in Ireland vary depending on the university and program. On average, tuition fees for international students range from 10,000 to 25,000 euros per year for undergraduate programs and from 10,000 to 35,000 euros per year for postgraduate programs. Living costs, including accommodation, food, and transportation, can range from 7,000 to 12,000 euros per year.
Do I need to speak Irish to study in Ireland?

No, proficiency in Irish is not required to study in Ireland. The majority of courses at Irish universities are taught in English, and international students are typically required to demonstrate proficiency in English through standardized tests such as the IELTS or TOEFL.
Are there scholarship opportunities for international students in Ireland?

Yes, there are scholarship opportunities available for international students to study in Ireland. The Irish government, through the Irish Research Council and other agencies, offers scholarships for research-based programs. Additionally, many universities and colleges in Ireland offer scholarships based on academic merit, leadership qualities, and other criteria.
Can I work while study in Ireland?

Yes, international students in Ireland are allowed to work part-time during the academic year (up to 20 hours per week) and full-time during holidays. However, it's important to note that your student visa will have specific conditions regarding work, so it's advisable to check with the Irish Naturalisation and Immigration Service (INIS) for the most up-to-date information.
